is Chief of Policy & Innovation at Right on Crime (www.rightoncrime.com), an initiative of the Texas Public Policy Foundation.
Perhaps unsurprisingly, extensive research has found periods of solitary confinement of 15 days or more lead to adverse psychological and physical health consequences.
Not only does prolonged solitary confinement increase the risk of suicide and death after release, but it also endangers public safety, as there are much higher rates of recidivism among those released from solitary confinement to society.
In light of these findings, many correctional systems have made significant headway in reducing the use of prolonged solitary confinement.
Incarceration is itself an isolating experience, but the use of solitary confinement effectively creates a prison within a prison.